wfDlsDelete.name: wfDlsDelete
wfDlsDelete.description: Create/Delete parameter. Default is created. Users perform an SNMP SET operation on this object in order to create/delete DLSw

wfDlsDisable.name: wfDlsDisable
wfDlsDisable.description: Enable/Disable parameter. Default is enabled. Users perform an SNMP SET operation on this object in order to enable/disable DLSw

wfDlsTcpWindowSize.name: wfDlsTcpWindowSize
wfDlsTcpWindowSize.description: The size in bytes of the windows used for the DLSw TCP connections

wfDlsVirtualRing.name: wfDlsVirtualRing
wfDlsVirtualRing.description: The virtual ring number for the TCP/IP cloud. Valid values (1-4095)

wfDlsInternalLanId.name: wfDlsInternalLanId
wfDlsInternalLanId.description: The source routing internal lan id. Valid Values (1-4095)

wfDlsBridgeId.name: wfDlsBridgeId
wfDlsBridgeId.description: The source routing base bridge number. Valid Values (1-15)

wfDlsMaxSlotSessions.name: wfDlsMaxSlotSessions
wfDlsMaxSlotSessions.description: The maximum number of LLC2 sessions to support per slot

wfDlsTotalCircuits.name: wfDlsTotalCircuits
wfDlsTotalCircuits.description: A current count of the total number of DLSw circuits established

wfDlsVirtualRingMtu.name: wfDlsVirtualRingMtu
wfDlsVirtualRingMtu.description: The MTU to use in explorers generated by this DLSw. It should reflect the minimum MTU size of the entire network including the remote LANs. Valid values (> 0)

wfDlsMacAgeTime.name: wfDlsMacAgeTime
wfDlsMacAgeTime.description: The time in seconds before inactive MAC addresses will be aged out of the cache. Valid values (> 20)

wfDlsNbAgeTime.name: wfDlsNbAgeTime
wfDlsNbAgeTime.description: The time in seconds before inactive NetBIOS names will be aged out of the cache. Valid values (> 20)

wfDlsUnconfPeerReject.name: wfDlsUnconfPeerReject
wfDlsUnconfPeerReject.description: Allow establishment of TCP connections from peers not in the Peer Table

wfDlsDebugLevel1.name: wfDlsDebugLevel1
wfDlsDebugLevel1.description: First Level debug flag. Cannot be configured with Site Manager. When this flag is set to Zero, no debug messages will be logged. Each bit of this flag represents certain functionality in DLSw. When this bit is set, all level2 elements that are part of this functionality that have their bits set will be allowed to log debug messages.

wfDlsDebugLevel2.name: wfDlsDebugLevel2
wfDlsDebugLevel2.description: Second Level debug flag. Cannot be configured with Site Manager. When this flag is set to Zero, no debug messages will be logged. Each bit of this flag represents a sub-functional element. When this bit is set, all debug messages in this element will be logged, as long as the related level1 functionality is set.

wfDlsWanKeepaliveTime.name: wfDlsWanKeepaliveTime
wfDlsWanKeepaliveTime.description: Keepalive packets will be sent into inactive, established TCP connections after this time interval (in seconds). A time of zero disables this keepalive feature.

wfDlsPPriDisable.name: wfDlsPPriDisable
wfDlsPPriDisable.description: Protocol Prioritization Enable/Disable parameter. Default is disabled. Users perform an SNMP SET operation to enable/disable this feature.

wfDlsPPriDefaultNumQueues.name: wfDlsPPriDefaultNumQueues
wfDlsPPriDefaultNumQueues.description: DLSw Prioritization Default number of Queues. The number of queues to be created when establishing a Peer connection if none have been previously defined. The default is two queues: queue number 0 and 1.

wfDlsPPriDefaultQBandwidth.name: wfDlsPPriDefaultQBandwidth
wfDlsPPriDefaultQBandwidth.description: DLSw Prioritization Default Queues Bandwidth. The bandwidth for each default queue. Default of: 60% queue 0, 40% queue 1 via site manager.

wfDlsPPriUnconfPeerDisable.name: wfDlsPPriUnconfPeerDisable
wfDlsPPriUnconfPeerDisable.description: DLSw Prioritization enabled/disabled for peers not in Peer Table.

wfDlsPPriUnconfPeerMaxQBuf.name: wfDlsPPriUnconfPeerMaxQBuf
wfDlsPPriUnconfPeerMaxQBuf.description: DLSw Prioritization enabled/disabled for peers not in Peer Table.

wfDlsPPriUnconfPeerMaxQSize.name: wfDlsPPriUnconfPeerMaxQSize
wfDlsPPriUnconfPeerMaxQSize.description: DLSw Prioritization enabled/disabled for peers not in Peer Table.

wfDlsPkgMaxSize.name: wfDlsPkgMaxSize
wfDlsPkgMaxSize.description: Maximum size of frame to sended over the WAN. Used when packaging multiple DLS frames into a single TCP frame. The value specified must be smaller than the wfDlsTcpWindowSize and should be no greater than the MTU for the WAN minus the size of the TCP/IP/MAC headers.

wfDlsPkgTO.name: wfDlsPkgTO
wfDlsPkgTO.description: DLSw packaging Time-out. Number of msec to delay a package before sending to TCP. This value should be based on the WAN speed wfDlsPkgWinPercent (defined below). This value should be no greater than the amount of time it takes to send the number of outstanding bytes before packaging begins: number bytes / (number bytes per msec) Default of 10 msec.

wfDlsPkgWinPercent.name: wfDlsPkgWinPercent
wfDlsPkgWinPercent.description: DLSw Packaging threshold. What percent of the DLS TCP window must be outstanding inorder to delay the sending of a package being built. Default: 20% of TCP window. Range: 0 - 100, with 0 meaning no delay.

wfDlsMultislotBcasts.name: wfDlsMultislotBcasts
wfDlsMultislotBcasts.description: Allow broadcasts inbound from the WAN to be broadcast to all active DLSw slots.

wfDlsInitialPacingWindow.name: wfDlsInitialPacingWindow
wfDlsInitialPacingWindow.description: Initial pacing window to be advertised in Capabilities Exchange messages. Adaptive pacing will begin with this value and use the state of the network to find the proper pacing window size.

wfDlsRfc.name: wfDlsRfc
wfDlsRfc.description: DLSw RFC mode selection. - RFC1434 is the original implementation - RFC1795 provides improved interoperability and flow control - v20_unicast supports Canureach Exploring via unicast UDP frames and provides single TCP connections - RFC2166 additionally supports Multicast Canureach Exploring

wfDlsWanKeepaliveRetryTimer.name: wfDlsWanKeepaliveRetryTimer
wfDlsWanKeepaliveRetryTimer.description: KEEPALIVE retransmit timeout period, in seconds. This is the interval at which unacknowledged KEEPALIVE messages will be retransmitted. If the Idle Timer is set to zero, this timer ignored. If the Idle Timer is non-zero and this timer IS zero, no KEEPALIVEs are sent and the session is terminated upon expiration of the Idle Timer.

wfDlsWanKeepaliveRetries.name: wfDlsWanKeepaliveRetries
wfDlsWanKeepaliveRetries.description: Number of unacknowledged KEEPALIVE messages retransmitted before the TCP session is terminated. If this count is set to zero, only one KEEPALIVE message will be sent.

wfDlsSnaFallbackAttempts.name: wfDlsSnaFallbackAttempts
wfDlsSnaFallbackAttempts.description: Number of times CANUREACH_ex will be sent (for SNA based connections) before attempting to fall back. Used for peers configured as wfDlsPeerTransportType = unknown to attempt connecting via RFC 1795.

wfDlsNetbiosFallbackTime.name: wfDlsNetbiosFallbackTime
wfDlsNetbiosFallbackTime.description: Amount of time in sec before falling back to RFC 1795 for the peers configured with wfDlsPeerTransportType = unknown, if NETBIOS_NQ does not get answered.

wfDlsTcpInactTime.name: wfDlsTcpInactTime
wfDlsTcpInactTime.description: Amount of time in sec after the last active DLSw circuit has terminated or there was no data transfered over TCP pipe, before bringing down TCP connection. Used in conjunction with wfDlsTcpInactMethod.

wfDlsTcpInactMethod.name: wfDlsTcpInactMethod
wfDlsTcpInactMethod.description: Determines when tcp connections may be brought down. Could be due to no DLS circuits on a peer, no data passing over the TCP link, or leave the TCP connection up. Used in conjunction with wfDlsTcpInactTime.

wfDlsMslotDLCBcasts.name: wfDlsMslotDLCBcasts
wfDlsMslotDLCBcasts.description: Allow broadcast messages inbound from the DLC to be sent to all active DLSw slots.

wfDlsRsvpSupport.name: wfDlsRsvpSupport
wfDlsRsvpSupport.description: Enables/Disables use of RSVP by DLSw

wfDlsOutBandwidth.name: wfDlsOutBandwidth
wfDlsOutBandwidth.description: Bandwidth amount for the outgoing DLSw traffic, to use in RSVP reservations for unconfigured peers

wfDlsOutBurstSize.name: wfDlsOutBurstSize
wfDlsOutBurstSize.description: Burst Size amount for the outgoing DLSw traffic, to use in RSVP reservations for unconfigured peers

wfDlsInBandwidth.name: wfDlsInBandwidth
wfDlsInBandwidth.description: Bandwidth amount for the incoming DLSw traffic, to use in RSVP reservations for unconfigured peers

wfDlsInBurstSize.name: wfDlsInBurstSize
wfDlsInBurstSize.description: Burst Size amount for the incoming DLSw traffic, to use in RSVP reservations for unconfigured peers

wfDlsNonPeakOutBandwidth.name: wfDlsNonPeakOutBandwidth
wfDlsNonPeakOutBandwidth.description: Bandwidth amount for the outgoing DLSw traffic, to use in RSVP reservations for unconfigured peers during non-peak hours

wfDlsNonPeakOutBurstSize.name: wfDlsNonPeakOutBurstSize
wfDlsNonPeakOutBurstSize.description: Burst Size amount for the outgoing DLSw traffic, to use in RSVP reservations for unconfigured peers during non-peak hours

wfDlsNonPeakInBandwidth.name: wfDlsNonPeakInBandwidth
wfDlsNonPeakInBandwidth.description: Bandwidth amount for the incoming DLSw traffic, to use in RSVP reservations for unconfigured peers during non-peak hours

wfDlsNonPeakInBurstSize.name: wfDlsNonPeakInBurstSize
wfDlsNonPeakInBurstSize.description: Burst Size amount for the incoming DLSw traffic, to use in RSVP reservations for unconfigured peers during non-peak hours

wfDlsNonPeakStartTime.name: wfDlsNonPeakStartTime
wfDlsNonPeakStartTime.description: Start time of the non-peak hours in hhmm format and 24 hour clock. If start time is greater in value than end time, non-peak hours ends the next day.

wfDlsNonPeakEndTime.name: wfDlsNonPeakEndTime
wfDlsNonPeakEndTime.description: End time of the non-peak hours in hhmm 24 hour clock format

wfDlsNonPeakStartDays.name: wfDlsNonPeakStartDays
wfDlsNonPeakStartDays.description: Bitmap of the starting days of the week for a non-peak reservations. The MSBit represents Sunday, the next most significant bit represents Monday, and so on... Default is 0 - non-peak parameters are not used.

wfDlsMultislotCacheUpdate.name: wfDlsMultislotCacheUpdate
wfDlsMultislotCacheUpdate.description: Allow learned MAC-IP cache resolutions to be promulgated to all other DLSw slots.

wfDlsMacAddrTranslation.name: wfDlsMacAddrTranslation
wfDlsMacAddrTranslation.description: Enables/Disables use of Mac Address Translation by DLSw

wfDlsBan2Support.name: wfDlsBan2Support
wfDlsBan2Support.description: Enables/Disables BAN-2 local termination between SRB interfaces in single DLS switch configs

wfDlsVirtualRingBridgeCheck.name: wfDlsVirtualRingBridgeCheck
wfDlsVirtualRingBridgeCheck.description: DLSw Virtual Ring ID and SRB Bridge ID will be checked.

wfDlsAcceptBadVendorSpecificCapex.name: wfDlsAcceptBadVendorSpecificCapex
wfDlsAcceptBadVendorSpecificCapex.description: Accept a capex request containing a Vendor Specific Control Vector but no Vendor Context. The Control Vector will be ignored

wfDlsDiagSwitch.name: wfDlsDiagSwitch
wfDlsDiagSwitch.description: Available MIB for diagnostic workspaces. Allows optional conditional debugging

wfDlsAllowSpecAddrNbDatagram.name: wfDlsAllowSpecAddrNbDatagram
wfDlsAllowSpecAddrNbDatagram.description: Allows acceptance of NETBIOS Datagrams sent to other than the NETBIOS Group address as the destination MAC address. This is an override MIB. When enabled, DLS will bypass its check for that group address and allow the packet.

wfDlsInterfaceTable.name: wfDlsInterfaceTable
wfDlsInterfaceTable.description: A table that contains information about every interface that is associated with DLSw inst_id[1] = wfDlsInterfaceCircuit

wfDlsInterfaceDelete.name: wfDlsInterfaceDelete
wfDlsInterfaceDelete.description: Create/Delete parameter. Default is created. Users perform an SNMP SET operation on this object in order to create/delete an interface

wfDlsInterfaceDisable.name: wfDlsInterfaceDisable
wfDlsInterfaceDisable.description: Enable/Disable parameter. Default is enabled. Users perform an SNMP SET operation on this object in order to enable/disable an interface

wfDlsInterfaceState.name: wfDlsInterfaceState
wfDlsInterfaceState.description: The current state of the interface

wfDlsInterfaceCircuit.name: wfDlsInterfaceCircuit
wfDlsInterfaceCircuit.description: The circuit that this interface runs over

wfDlsInterfaceBridgeId.name: wfDlsInterfaceBridgeId
wfDlsInterfaceBridgeId.description: The Bridge Id of the 'bridge' from the internal Lan to the TCP/IP ring. This must be a non-Wellfleet bridge number. Valid Values (1-15)

wfDlsInterfaceLanId.name: wfDlsInterfaceLanId
wfDlsInterfaceLanId.description: The Lan Id of the interface. Valid Values (1-4095)

wfDlsInterfaceDlcType.name: wfDlsInterfaceDlcType
wfDlsInterfaceDlcType.description: The Data Link Control Type on this interface.

wfDlsInterfaceSdlcMode.name: wfDlsInterfaceSdlcMode
wfDlsInterfaceSdlcMode.description: The SDLC Mode on this interface.

wfDlsInterfaceNbBcastDgramReduce.name: wfDlsInterfaceNbBcastDgramReduce
wfDlsInterfaceNbBcastDgramReduce.description: This allows the NetBios Broadcast dgram reduction code built into dls to be turned off.

wfDlsInterfaceExplorerType.name: wfDlsInterfaceExplorerType
wfDlsInterfaceExplorerType.description: This allows CANUREACH test frames to be sent as single-route or all-routes explorer frames.

wfDlsInterfaceNbBcastDgramCache.name: wfDlsInterfaceNbBcastDgramCache
wfDlsInterfaceNbBcastDgramCache.description: This allows Netbios Broadcast datagram frames to be cached along with allowing these same frames to utilize the netbios caching mechanism. Value 1 means feature not on. Value 2 means if frame is not in cache then forward it. Value 3 means if frame is not in cache then drop it.

wfDlsInterfaceClrCallEnable.name: wfDlsInterfaceClrCallEnable
wfDlsInterfaceClrCallEnable.description: This allows a generic (e.g. QLLC/X25) call to be cleared when the DLS connection enters a DISCONNECTED state.

wfDlsSlotTable.name: wfDlsSlotTable
wfDlsSlotTable.description: A table that contains the IP interfaces each slot must use for the TCP connections to non-Wellfleet switches. The IP interface may exist anywhere on the box. inst_id[1] = wfDlsSlotNumber

wfDlsSlotDelete.name: wfDlsSlotDelete
wfDlsSlotDelete.description: Create/Delete parameter. Default is created. Users perform an SNMP SET operation on this object in order to create/delete a DLSw slot IP record

wfDlsSlotNumber.name: wfDlsSlotNumber
wfDlsSlotNumber.description: The slot that uses this IP interface

wfDlsSlotIpAddr.name: wfDlsSlotIpAddr
wfDlsSlotIpAddr.description: The IP interface to use for TCP connections based on this slot

wfDlsCurrentMemory.name: wfDlsCurrentMemory
wfDlsCurrentMemory.description: Memory currently available on this slot

wfDlsMaxAllowedMemory.name: wfDlsMaxAllowedMemory
wfDlsMaxAllowedMemory.description: Maximum amount of memory allowed to be allocated for DLS on this slot. 4294967295 = 0xFFFFFFFF stands for infinite. (i.e. all available memory)

wfDlsHiWaterMark.name: wfDlsHiWaterMark
wfDlsHiWaterMark.description: This is the maximum amount of memory ever allocated by DLS on this slot since the last boot

wfDlsSlotGenDestination.name: wfDlsSlotGenDestination
wfDlsSlotGenDestination.description: This is a destination slot of the GEN tool if the value is 0. For any non-zero number, the slot is a GEN source and the value of wfDlsSlotGenDestination is its destination slot.

wfDlsSlotGenSessions.name: wfDlsSlotGenSessions
wfDlsSlotGenSessions.description: The maximum number of Generator sessions to support per slot

wfDlsSlotGenUpperMAC.name: wfDlsSlotGenUpperMAC
wfDlsSlotGenUpperMAC.description: The upper MAC address for this slot.

wfDlsSlotCurrentSessions.name: wfDlsSlotCurrentSessions
wfDlsSlotCurrentSessions.description: The number of sessions connected on this slot.

wfDlsSlotHiWaterSessions.name: wfDlsSlotHiWaterSessions
wfDlsSlotHiWaterSessions.description: The highest number of sessions connected at one time on this slot.

wfDlsSlotHiWaterReset.name: wfDlsSlotHiWaterReset
wfDlsSlotHiWaterReset.description: Setting to 2 (reset) sets HiWaterSessions to CurrentSessions.

wfDlsSapTable.name: wfDlsSapTable
wfDlsSapTable.description: A table that contains the SAPS to be terminated by DLSw. inst_id[1] = wfDlsSapAddr

wfDlsSapDelete.name: wfDlsSapDelete
wfDlsSapDelete.description: Create/Delete parameter. Default is created. Users perform an SNMP SET operation on this object in order to create/delete a DLSw SAP record

wfDlsSapAddr.name: wfDlsSapAddr
wfDlsSapAddr.description: The SAP to be terminated by DLSw

wfDlsSapCredit.name: wfDlsSapCredit
wfDlsSapCredit.description: The LLC2 flow control credit size for this SAP. Flow control procedures will be invoked based on this parameter

wfDlsPeerTable.name: wfDlsPeerTable
wfDlsPeerTable.description: A table that contains the IP addresses of the DLSw peers with which we will establish TCP connections. inst_id[4] = wfDlsPeerAddr

wfDlsPeerDelete.name: wfDlsPeerDelete
wfDlsPeerDelete.description: Create/Delete parameter. Default is created. Users perform an SNMP SET operation on this object in order to create/delete a DLSw peer record

wfDlsPeerState.name: wfDlsPeerState
wfDlsPeerState.description: The current state of the TCP connection with this DLSw peer

wfDlsPeerIpAddr.name: wfDlsPeerIpAddr
wfDlsPeerIpAddr.description: The IP address of the DLSw peer

wfDlsPeerDefinedBy.name: wfDlsPeerDefinedBy
wfDlsPeerDefinedBy.description: The method by which this peer was defined

wfDlsPeerPPriDisable.name: wfDlsPeerPPriDisable
wfDlsPeerPPriDisable.description: DLSw Protocol Priority enabled/disabled for this Peer. The default is to use the value specified in the DLS Base record (wfDlsPPriDisable). Site Manager handles the setting of the default.

wfDlsPeerPPriMaxQBuf.name: wfDlsPeerPPriMaxQBuf
wfDlsPeerPPriMaxQBuf.description: Protocol Priority Queue Maximum number of allocated buffers queued.

wfDlsPeerPPriMaxQSize.name: wfDlsPeerPPriMaxQSize
wfDlsPeerPPriMaxQSize.description: Protocol Priority Queue Maximum number of octets queued.

wfDlsPeerPPriClearStats.name: wfDlsPeerPPriClearStats
wfDlsPeerPPriClearStats.description: Clear Protocol Priority Statistics. If prioritization is enabled for this Peer, then modifying this attribute will cause all Statistics kept (Queue's, CC, etc) to be cleared.

wfDlsPeerType.name: wfDlsPeerType
wfDlsPeerType.description: The protocol type of this DLSw peer

wfDlsPeerTransportType.name: wfDlsPeerTransportType
wfDlsPeerTransportType.description: The transport type of this DLSw peer

wfDlsPeerBackupConfig.name: wfDlsPeerBackupConfig
wfDlsPeerBackupConfig.description: The indication of whether or not a backup peer is to be configured for the primary peer. The default is no which means that there is no backup peer configured by default. A backup peer can only be configured for a RFC1434 or RFC1795 peer.

wfDlsPeerBackupIpAddr.name: wfDlsPeerBackupIpAddr
wfDlsPeerBackupIpAddr.description: The IP Address of the backup DLSw peer.

wfDlsPeerBackupMaxUpTime.name: wfDlsPeerBackupMaxUpTime
wfDlsPeerBackupMaxUpTime.description: The maximum amount of time (in seconds) allowed for a TCP connection to stay established to the backup DLSw peer. If set to zero, this feature is disabled. Set to anything greater than zero to enable the feature.

wfDlsPeerBackupHoldDownTime.name: wfDlsPeerBackupHoldDownTime
wfDlsPeerBackupHoldDownTime.description: The amount of time (in seconds) to wait before starting a new TCP connection to the backup DLSw peer.

wfDlsPeerBackupStartTime.name: wfDlsPeerBackupStartTime
wfDlsPeerBackupStartTime.description: Used in conjunction with the EndTime attribute. Together these define a time interval for when a backup peer can be active. The start time is the beginning time of day that a backup peer can be established. (HHMM format)

wfDlsPeerBackupEndTime.name: wfDlsPeerBackupEndTime
wfDlsPeerBackupEndTime.description: Used in conjunction with the StartTime attribute. Together these define a time interval for when a backup peer can be active. The end time is the end time of day that a backup peer can be established. If a backup peer is active and the current time is after this end time, the backup peer will be brought down. (HHMM format)

wfDlsPeerInteroperability.name: wfDlsPeerInteroperability
wfDlsPeerInteroperability.description: If enabled, open write to read tcp connection for 1434 and 1795 type of peers. Let the other side to open the other connection.

wfDlsPeerBackupType.name: wfDlsPeerBackupType
wfDlsPeerBackupType.description: The type of this DLSw backup peer

wfDlsPeerRsvpMode.name: wfDlsPeerRsvpMode
wfDlsPeerRsvpMode.description: Defines rsvp mode of operation for the peer: - 1 use rsvp parameters configured in the peer; - 2 do NOT use rsvp for this peer; - 3 use rsvp parameters configures in wfDls object.

wfDlsPeerRsvpSlots.name: wfDlsPeerRsvpSlots
wfDlsPeerRsvpSlots.description: Bit mask field representing the slots, that may make RSVP resevations for this peer. The MSBit represents slot 1, the next most significant bit represents slot 2, and so on... Slots can be 1-14. Default is all slots on a BCN.

wfDlsPeerOutBandwidth.name: wfDlsPeerOutBandwidth
wfDlsPeerOutBandwidth.description: Bandwidth amount for the outgoing DLSw traffic, to use in RSVP reservations for this peer

wfDlsPeerOutBurstSize.name: wfDlsPeerOutBurstSize
wfDlsPeerOutBurstSize.description: Burst Size amount for the outgoing DLSw traffic, to use in RSVP reservations for this peer

wfDlsPeerInBandwidth.name: wfDlsPeerInBandwidth
wfDlsPeerInBandwidth.description: Bandwidth amount for the incoming DLSw traffic, to use in RSVP reservations for this peer

wfDlsPeerInBurstSize.name: wfDlsPeerInBurstSize
wfDlsPeerInBurstSize.description: Burst Size amount for the incoming DLSw traffic, to use in RSVP reservations for this peer

wfDlsPeerNonPeakOutBandwidth.name: wfDlsPeerNonPeakOutBandwidth
wfDlsPeerNonPeakOutBandwidth.description: Bandwidth amount for the outgoing DLSw traffic, to use in RSVP reservations for this peer during non-peak hours

wfDlsPeerNonPeakOutBurstSize.name: wfDlsPeerNonPeakOutBurstSize
wfDlsPeerNonPeakOutBurstSize.description: Burst Size amount for the outgoing DLSw traffic, to use in RSVP reservations for this peer during non-peak hours

wfDlsPeerNonPeakInBandwidth.name: wfDlsPeerNonPeakInBandwidth
wfDlsPeerNonPeakInBandwidth.description: Bandwidth amount for the incoming DLSw traffic, to use in RSVP reservations for this peer during non-peak hours

wfDlsPeerNonPeakInBurstSize.name: wfDlsPeerNonPeakInBurstSize
wfDlsPeerNonPeakInBurstSize.description: Burst Size amount for the incoming DLSw traffic, to use in RSVP reservations for this peer during non-peak hours

wfDlsPeerNonPeakStartTime.name: wfDlsPeerNonPeakStartTime
wfDlsPeerNonPeakStartTime.description: Start time of the non-peak hours in hhmm format and 24 hour clock. If start time is greater in value than end time, non-peak hours ends the next day.

wfDlsPeerNonPeakEndTime.name: wfDlsPeerNonPeakEndTime
wfDlsPeerNonPeakEndTime.description: End time of the non-peak hours in hhmm 24 hour clock format

wfDlsPeerNonPeakStartDays.name: wfDlsPeerNonPeakStartDays
wfDlsPeerNonPeakStartDays.description: Bitmap of the starting days of the week for a non-peak reservations. The MSBit represents Sunday, the next most significant bit represents Monday, and so on... Default is 0 - non-peak parameters are not used.

wfDlsPeerBackupOutBandwidth.name: wfDlsPeerBackupOutBandwidth
wfDlsPeerBackupOutBandwidth.description: Bandwidth amount for the outgoing DLSw traffic, to use in RSVP reservations for the backup peer

wfDlsPeerBackupOutBurstSize.name: wfDlsPeerBackupOutBurstSize
wfDlsPeerBackupOutBurstSize.description: Burst Size amount for the outgoing DLSw traffic, to use in RSVP reservations for the backup peer

wfDlsPeerBackupInBandwidth.name: wfDlsPeerBackupInBandwidth
wfDlsPeerBackupInBandwidth.description: Bandwidth amount for the incoming DLSw traffic, to use in RSVP reservations for the backup peer

wfDlsPeerBackupInBurstSize.name: wfDlsPeerBackupInBurstSize
wfDlsPeerBackupInBurstSize.description: Burst Size amount for the incoming DLSw traffic, to use in RSVP reservations for the backup peer

wfDlsConnectionTable.name: wfDlsConnectionTable
wfDlsConnectionTable.description: A table that contains the information about the current DLSw connections in progress. inst_id[15] = wfDlsConnectionCct wfDlsConnectionSrcMac wfDlsConnectionDstMac wfDlsConnectionSaps

wfDlsConnectionCct.name: wfDlsConnectionCct
wfDlsConnectionCct.description: The circuit this from which this connection originated

wfDlsConnectionDstMac.name: wfDlsConnectionDstMac
wfDlsConnectionDstMac.description: The Destination MAC address (the LLC session target)

wfDlsConnectionSrcMac.name: wfDlsConnectionSrcMac
wfDlsConnectionSrcMac.description: The Source MAC address (the LLC session originator)

wfDlsConnectionSaps.name: wfDlsConnectionSaps
wfDlsConnectionSaps.description: The SAPs for this connection (DSAP, SSAP)

wfDlsConnectionState.name: wfDlsConnectionState
wfDlsConnectionState.description: The DLSw state of this connection. These are the steady states of the DLSw state machine. Transition states are not reflected

wfDlsConnectionRemoteIpAddr.name: wfDlsConnectionRemoteIpAddr
wfDlsConnectionRemoteIpAddr.description: The IP address of the remote DLSw peer over which this connection is established

wfDlsConnectionRemoteRxPort.name: wfDlsConnectionRemoteRxPort
wfDlsConnectionRemoteRxPort.description: The TCP receive port number of the remote DLSw peer over which this connection is established

wfDlsConnectionLocalIpAddr.name: wfDlsConnectionLocalIpAddr
wfDlsConnectionLocalIpAddr.description: The IP address of the local DLSw peer over which this connection is established

wfDlsConnectionLocalTxPort.name: wfDlsConnectionLocalTxPort
wfDlsConnectionLocalTxPort.description: The TCP transmit port number of the local DLSw peer over which this connection is established

wfDlsConnectionTxIFrames.name: wfDlsConnectionTxIFrames
wfDlsConnectionTxIFrames.description: The number of Information frames transmitted from this switch to the remote DLSw switch

wfDlsConnectionRxIFrames.name: wfDlsConnectionRxIFrames
wfDlsConnectionRxIFrames.description: The number of Information frames received at this switch from the remote DLSw switch

wfDlsConnectionTxRnrs.name: wfDlsConnectionTxRnrs
wfDlsConnectionTxRnrs.description: The number of RNR frames transmitted from this switch to the remote DLSw switch

wfDlsConnectionRxRnrs.name: wfDlsConnectionRxRnrs
wfDlsConnectionRxRnrs.description: The number of RNR frames received at this switch from the remote DLSw switch

wfDlsConnectionLocalBlockNum.name: wfDlsConnectionLocalBlockNum
wfDlsConnectionLocalBlockNum.description: The block number is the first 3 hexadecimal digits of node identification field of local XID

wfDlsConnectionLocalIdNum.name: wfDlsConnectionLocalIdNum
wfDlsConnectionLocalIdNum.description: The ID number is the last 5 hexadecimal digits of node identification field of local XID

wfDlsConnectionRemoteBlockNum.name: wfDlsConnectionRemoteBlockNum
wfDlsConnectionRemoteBlockNum.description: The block number is the first 3 hexadecimal digits of node identification field of remote XID

wfDlsConnectionRemoteIdNum.name: wfDlsConnectionRemoteIdNum

wfDlsLocalDeviceCanureachTimer.name: wfDlsLocalDeviceCanureachTimer
wfDlsLocalDeviceCanureachTimer.description: The time interval in seconds that a canureach is sent to the remote DLS peer to establish a session. A minimum value of 1 means that a canureach will be transmitted once a second, a maximum value of 3600 means that a canureach will be transmitted once an hour, and a value of 0 means that no canureach will be transmitted

wfDlsLocalDeviceCanureachRetries.name: wfDlsLocalDeviceCanureachRetries
wfDlsLocalDeviceCanureachRetries.description: The maximum number of times a canureach is sent to the remote DLS peer to establish a session. A minimum value of 0 means that no canureach messages will be transmitted, a maximum value of 0xFFFFFFFF means that an infinite number of canureach messages will be transmitted for this connection. The default is set to 10

wfDlsLocalDeviceLSTimer.name: wfDlsLocalDeviceLSTimer
wfDlsLocalDeviceLSTimer.description: The time interval in seconds that a connect request is sent to the local SDLC device to establish a session. A minimum value of 1 means that a connect request will be sent once a second, a maximum value of 3600 means that a connect request will be sent once an hour, and a value of 0 means that no connect requests will be sent

wfDlsLocalDeviceLSRetries.name: wfDlsLocalDeviceLSRetries
wfDlsLocalDeviceLSRetries.description: The maximum number of times a connect request is sent to the local SDLC device to establish a session. A minimum value of 0 means that no connect requests will be sent, a maximum value of 0xFFFFFFFF means that an infinite number of connect requests will be sent for this connection. The default is set to 10

wfDlsLocalDeviceRcvCredit.name: wfDlsLocalDeviceRcvCredit
wfDlsLocalDeviceRcvCredit.description: Receive credit count. Maximum number of frames SDLC is allowed to send to DLS. A minimum value of 1 means that DLS will only accept up to 1 frame from SDLC before it updates SDLCs credit. A value of 0 means that DLS can receive an infinite number of frames from SDLC without the need to update SDLC's credit

wfDlsLocalDeviceTxCredit.name: wfDlsLocalDeviceTxCredit
wfDlsLocalDeviceTxCredit.description: Transmit credit count. Maximum number of frames DLS is allowed to send to SDLC. A minimum value of 1 means that DLS can only send one frame to SDLC until it receives credit update from SDLC. A value of 0 means that DLS can send an infinite number of frames to SDLC without the need to update SDLC's credit

wfDlsLocalDeviceCurTimer2.name: wfDlsLocalDeviceCurTimer2
wfDlsLocalDeviceCurTimer2.description: The time interval in seconds that a canureach is sent to the remote DLS peer to establish a session. A minimum value of 1 means that a canureach will be transmitted once a second, a maximum value means that a canureach will be transmitted once every timer2 seconds, and a value of 0 means that no canureach will be transmitted

wfDlsLocalDeviceCurRetries2.name: wfDlsLocalDeviceCurRetries2
wfDlsLocalDeviceCurRetries2.description: The maximum number of times a canureach is sent to the remote DLS peer to establish a session. A minimum value of 0 means that no canureach messages will be transmitted, a maximum value of 0xFFFFFFFF means that an infinite number of canureach messages will be transmitted for this connection. The default is set to infinite: 4294967295 = 0xFFFFFFFF

wfDlsLocalDeviceEnableXidPassthru.name: wfDlsLocalDeviceEnableXidPassthru
wfDlsLocalDeviceEnableXidPassthru.description: XID passthru Enable/Disable parameter. Default is enabled. Used for pu2.1 circuits to allow the XID to be passed thru to SDLC when host is connected to token ring and remote is SDLC.

wfDlsLocalDeviceActivationSequence.name: wfDlsLocalDeviceActivationSequence
wfDlsLocalDeviceActivationSequence.description: Sequence of activation for SDLC PU2.0 fixed format primary devices. LocalDeviceFirst specifies that DLS establishes a connection with the SDLC End Station first. Once the Local Device successfully responds, DLS then starts up the SSP connection to the peer. PeerFirst specifies that DLS starts the SSP connection first, and contacts the SDLC End Station only after receiving a CONTACT message from the peer.

Inactive indicates that DLSw in not a member of this multicast IP group. The initial state is notpresent and this state will be maintained until this mib record has been read.

The end time is the end time of day that a backup peer can be established. If a backup peer is active and the current time is after this end time, the backup peer will be brought down. (HHMM format)
